          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          <strong>🇷🇺 Putin is ready for peace, but not with Zelenskky</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Vladimir Putin remarked that Russia is <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-01-2025-br1-10-open-to-peace-talks" target="_blank">open to peace talks</a> with Ukraine but ruled out direct negotiations with President Volodymyr Zelenskyy. He also called the Ukrainian leader "illegitimate" since his presidential term expired last year during martial law. He suggested alternative Ukrainian representatives could negotiate but insisted any deal must align with Russia's interests.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Putin also claims the war would end in two months if Western support for Ukraine stops. <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-01-2025-br1-11-zelenskyy-responded" target="_blank">Zelensky responded</a>, accusing Putin of using "cynical tricks" to prolong the war. President Trump has pressured both sides to negotiate while threatening stricter sanctions on Russia. Kyiv, however, warned against being sidelined in potential US-Russia talks, accusing Putin of attempting to manipulate Trump to secure a favorable settlement.</p>
        </mj-text>
